1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,413
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arhato Sambha Sambhu Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arhato Sambha Sambhu Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arhato Sambha Sambhu Dasa

2
00:00:29,393 --> 00:00:33,759
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:37,985 --> 00:00:57,594
Normally, today, because we're celebrating the Buddha, I would normally spend most of the time just describing his life and what set him off on his path and what he eventually achieved.

4
00:00:58,012 --> 00:00:59,655
It'll come into it, what I'm saying.

5
00:01:00,316 --> 00:01:09,265
But I thought this time we'd concentrate just a little bit more upon endgame, upon exactly where we're supposed to be going.

6
00:01:15,893 --> 00:01:16,853
I'll read this out.

7
00:01:17,915 --> 00:01:22,519
These are synonyms, adjectives for nibbana.

8
00:01:23,740 --> 00:01:25,302
So he starts by saying to them,

9
00:01:25,739 --> 00:01:31,483
I will teach you the unconditioned and the path leading to the unconditioned.

10
00:01:31,504 --> 00:01:33,206
And what monks is the unconditioned?

11
00:01:33,506 --> 00:01:37,969
The destruction of lust, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion.

12
00:01:38,450 --> 00:01:40,451
This is called the unconditioned.

13
00:01:41,632 --> 00:01:44,436
And what monk is the path leading to the unconditioned?

14
00:01:45,316 --> 00:01:47,298
Mindfulness directed to the body.

15
00:01:47,539 --> 00:01:50,141
This is called the path leading to the unconditioned.

16
00:01:51,182 --> 00:01:53,703
And then he talks about...

17
00:01:53,920 --> 00:01:57,025
He's describing what this unconditioned is.

18
00:01:57,045 --> 00:02:17,379
I will teach you the uninclined, the taintless, the truth, the far shore, the subtle, the very difficult to see, the unaging, the stable, the undisintegrating, the unmanifest, the unproliferated,

19
00:02:17,949 --> 00:02:45,895
the peaceful, the deathless, the sublime, the auspicious, the secure, the destruction of craving, the wonderful, the amazing, the unhailing, the unhailing state, nibbana, the unafflicted, dispassion, purity, freedom, non-attachment, the island, the shelter, the asylum, the refuge, the destination and the path leading to that destination.

20
00:02:46,456 --> 00:02:47,518
And doesn't that make you want to go?

21
00:02:48,983 --> 00:02:50,685
Enough there, isn't there?

22
00:02:50,705 --> 00:02:52,227
And what, monks, is the destination?

23
00:02:52,347 --> 00:02:57,935
So the destination is the destruction of lust, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion.

24
00:02:57,974 --> 00:03:00,478
This is called the destination.

25
00:03:00,497 --> 00:03:02,600
And then he basically repeats himself.

26
00:03:05,424 --> 00:03:16,998
So in order to sort of grasp that in some way, we have to go back to his own particular experience.

27
00:03:17,705 --> 00:03:23,409
So remember that he's left a household life.

28
00:03:24,191 --> 00:03:34,219
And what's meant by that is that he's not searching for any end of suffering in what we would call the ordinary pleasures and delights of the world.

29
00:03:35,382 --> 00:03:39,365
So something there has undermined his confidence that that's possible.

30
00:03:40,667 --> 00:03:47,592
In those days, of course, they would have believed quite easily that there was a process of reincarnation

31
00:03:48,264 --> 00:03:56,034
And although there were materialists, what we would call materialists, that you just had a body and it died and that was the end of that.

32
00:03:57,477 --> 00:04:08,030
And that there would have been many teachers who would have explained how to achieve higher realms of existence and some idea that there was an end to it.

33
00:04:09,012 --> 00:04:15,419
At that time, there were the scriptures written by what we now call Hinduism.

34
00:04:16,091 --> 00:04:25,583
And they were beginning to understand that there was something that was unnameable, something that was transcendent.

35
00:04:26,684 --> 00:04:34,434
It was that, you know, people, one or two teachers in their scriptures had come to that conclusion through their own practice.

36
00:04:36,014 --> 00:04:45,146
So when the Buddha set out, there was already a ground of understanding and a huge history of practice.

37
00:04:45,165 --> 00:04:45,947
How far back?

38
00:04:46,348 --> 00:04:47,069
We don't know.

39
00:04:47,110 --> 00:04:52,617
Some think it goes back to the Indus Valley civilization, the yoga practice.

40
00:04:52,637 --> 00:04:53,718
But it has deep roots.

41
00:04:54,499 --> 00:05:02,870
And what he learned from his teachers is basically how to establish very beautiful states of mind that we now call the jhanas, the absorptions.

42
00:05:03,690 --> 00:05:07,514
These, of course, you find in all religions, ecstasies.

43
00:05:08,877 --> 00:05:15,225
And you get them through the practice of prayer, mantra, watching the breath.

44
00:05:15,778 --> 00:05:30,394
anything which calms and steadies you, anything which creates a delight, such as metta, metta practice, loving-kindness practice, that would eventually begin to develop in your very beautiful state, such that you would absorb into it.

45
00:05:30,413 --> 00:05:34,317
And there are deep enough states where you even lose contact with the world around you.

46
00:05:34,918 --> 00:05:43,187
So these absorptions were something that he became an expert at, and was invited by his teachers to join them, twice.

47
00:05:44,146 --> 00:05:57,064
So it was such practices seemingly were quite easy for him because it said that he left home when he was 29 and he was already liberated by the time he was 35.

48
00:05:57,663 --> 00:05:59,005
That's only six years, I can say.

49
00:05:59,766 --> 00:06:05,394
And he spent four of those years in practicing these self-mortifications.

50
00:06:06,302 --> 00:06:16,793
So that was on the understanding that the soul, the eternal spirit within us, was locked into the body by its past actions.

51
00:06:17,033 --> 00:06:22,959
So the body itself was an expression of past unwholesome deeds.

52
00:06:23,160 --> 00:06:26,764
In other words, your unwholesome karma.

53
00:06:26,783 --> 00:06:35,752
And for this spirit, this soul to be released back up into an eternal heaven, you have to somehow reduce the body.

54
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:37,702
to let go of the body.

55
00:06:38,363 --> 00:06:47,175
And so you've got these mortification exercises, seemingly a lot of them based around not eating, you see.

56
00:06:48,276 --> 00:06:52,382
And the Jain leader was one of the teachers of that.

57
00:06:53,043 --> 00:06:58,110
And the idea was that eventually, in Jainism, you just, well, you die.

58
00:06:58,771 --> 00:07:01,774
And that's your, and you've completely let go of the body.

59
00:07:02,516 --> 00:07:04,879
So when the Buddha tried this,

60
00:07:05,146 --> 00:07:08,369
So he would have only been in his 30s, yeah?

61
00:07:08,389 --> 00:07:10,411
He just found that he just created more suffering.

62
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:22,982
It didn't sort of help him overcome this internal questioning that he had, which we would now recognize as some sort of existential crisis.

63
00:07:23,023 --> 00:07:24,824
You know, what's the meaning of life?

64
00:07:24,884 --> 00:07:25,785
Why am I alive?

65
00:07:25,944 --> 00:07:26,805
Et cetera, et cetera.

66
00:07:27,165 --> 00:07:34,392
So it would have come with a sense of despair, a sense of frustration and so on.

67
00:07:34,593 --> 00:07:39,298
He left that, and he left his companions, who didn't like him for doing that.

68
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:41,002
They thought he was on soft and all that.

69
00:07:41,862 --> 00:07:53,798
And then remember that there's this occasion when he remembers about something from his childhood, which awakens in him some sort of turnaround upon his practice.

70
00:07:54,439 --> 00:08:02,271
So whereas before, like many of the people around him, the ascetics around him, was about gaining something, getting something,

71
00:08:02,656 --> 00:08:12,367
the practices were about achieving something, it made him turn around upon himself and begin to investigate exactly how he was creating suffering.

72
00:08:12,387 --> 00:08:14,850
This is what it turned out.

73
00:08:15,291 --> 00:08:24,524
Instead of trying to get rid of his mental anguish, he actually began to feel it, to watch it.

74
00:08:25,444 --> 00:08:31,211
And in which case, eventually, he saw the whole process whereby he creates suffering for himself.

75
00:08:31,968 --> 00:08:33,889
And that's this dependent origination.

76
00:08:35,672 --> 00:08:44,660
You might say that's the core of his teachings, that he was able to define clearly where the problem lay.

77
00:08:45,542 --> 00:08:52,009
And in the Four Noble Truths, as you know, he states that the cause of suffering is this desire.

78
00:08:52,649 --> 00:08:54,030
It's a specific desire.

79
00:08:54,211 --> 00:09:00,878
It's a desire about trying to get happiness from various sources, trying to be happy.

80
00:09:01,398 --> 00:09:08,817
but always based on a sort of profound misunderstanding, which he called the self.

81
00:09:08,837 --> 00:09:14,934
And the whole teaching centered at a deeper level about this sense of identity we have.

82
00:09:16,282 --> 00:09:28,840
So here we've got a sort of trajectory of going into ourselves, of seeing the psychological mechanisms whereby we create these problems within ourselves.

83
00:09:28,860 --> 00:09:32,926
And then, as it were, to go deeper in that and to seek the builder.

84
00:09:33,427 --> 00:09:36,090
So, I forgot to get my little book out here.

85
00:09:38,533 --> 00:09:43,280
So we chant in the morning, this is called his victory verse.

86
00:09:43,301 --> 00:09:44,802
And that's what it's...

87
00:09:45,491 --> 00:09:46,413
It's put down to.

88
00:09:47,394 --> 00:09:54,923
So I've traveled the round through the round of countless rebirths, seeking but not finding the house builder.

89
00:09:56,046 --> 00:09:58,068
How painful is birth over and over again.

90
00:09:58,408 --> 00:10:00,892
But oh, house builder, you've now been caught.

91
00:10:01,092 --> 00:10:02,634
You shall not build a house again.

92
00:10:03,075 --> 00:10:06,580
Your raft of the broken, your ridge pole demolished.

93
00:10:07,039 --> 00:10:12,748
The unconditioned consciousness has been attained and every kind of craving has been destroyed.

94
00:10:13,386 --> 00:10:21,216
So you can see here in that short little verse that he's got right down to the core of the problem.

95
00:10:21,738 --> 00:10:34,073
And there are many, all these adjectives are pointing to certain qualities about what happens to us when we finally get, undermine that basic misunderstanding.

96
00:10:36,015 --> 00:10:41,823
So when you look at his teachings, you see that they divide fairly clearly between

97
00:10:42,192 --> 00:10:51,221
all those what we would call morality or ethics or how to behave and this transcendence.

98
00:10:51,240 --> 00:10:55,725
And to understand that, we have to go back to this sense of self.

99
00:10:57,025 --> 00:11:02,071
So this is not the self of pride or the self of embarrassment.

100
00:11:02,812 --> 00:11:07,537
It's that pure sense of being here, which you get when you're sitting.

101
00:11:07,956 --> 00:11:10,038
So when you're sitting quietly like this,

102
00:11:10,423 --> 00:11:15,913
And you're pulling away from the body, heart and mind within yourself, you might say.

103
00:11:16,214 --> 00:11:22,884
And you feel yourself to be this observer, the feeler, the one who knows, the one who's experiencing things.

104
00:11:24,368 --> 00:11:29,475
So that sense of self there is the beginning of the problem.

105
00:11:29,535 --> 00:11:33,562
It's the first object that we make, the sense of me.

106
00:11:34,032 --> 00:11:41,222
So every time you get in the morning, you're awakened to this idea, oh, this is me, I'm here, I'm here.

107
00:11:41,243 --> 00:11:54,162
Just now I woke up, I must be tired from that travelling yesterday, because I woke up in the middle of the day, just after this little kip, after my little siesta, and had one of those lovely moments of wondering where I was.

108
00:11:56,966 --> 00:12:00,711
I suddenly realised it's midday and I've got to get out there and give a talk, oh my God.

109
00:12:00,730 --> 00:12:01,272
So...

110
00:12:01,740 --> 00:12:15,596
So a sense of not knowing who you are or what you are is one of those lovely little moments where we see how that creates within us such a disturbance, such a search for identity.

111
00:12:16,356 --> 00:12:22,764
So now that self is a relationship.

112
00:12:22,783 --> 00:12:27,187
It's a relationship that I have with my sense of being here.

113
00:12:27,788 --> 00:12:28,809
I am here.

114
00:12:29,370 --> 00:12:31,393
I've got this sense of me being here.

115
00:12:31,626 --> 00:12:40,039
And of course, me being here is within this psychophysical organism, but it's also in the world.

116
00:12:40,801 --> 00:12:44,947
And the natural drive is to be happy.

117
00:12:45,469 --> 00:12:57,988
I mean, you could say that you can see that run through even animals, ordinary animals and the animal kingdom that everybody, all sentient beings just want to be happy.

118
00:12:58,879 --> 00:13:02,485
Of course, how you define happiness is entirely idiosyncratic.

119
00:13:02,504 --> 00:13:03,527
I mean, it's just up to you.

120
00:13:04,008 --> 00:13:08,333
Some people are happy, you know, just chewing liquorice all day.

121
00:13:09,254 --> 00:13:14,322
But how you define happiness will be your goal, will be your aim, you see.

122
00:13:16,046 --> 00:13:24,398
And what the Buddha is pointing out is that all these aims, all these objectives we have are about relationship.

123
00:13:24,580 --> 00:13:30,346
So everything he's talking about is based upon ethics, upon relationship.

124
00:13:30,365 --> 00:13:39,035
And he points out that there are some relationships we have, even with biscuits, which can cause us lots of problems.

125
00:13:39,395 --> 00:13:42,720
And there are some relationships that are very supportive and help us.

126
00:13:43,200 --> 00:13:53,912
So it's a case of navigating our path through this sort of distinction between, well, what is wholesome for me and what is unwholesome for me?

127
00:13:54,618 --> 00:13:56,179
Now, most things are pretty clear.

128
00:13:56,220 --> 00:14:00,184
I mean, everybody knows you're going around murdering people or something like that.

129
00:14:00,785 --> 00:14:17,145
But when it gets to just the subtle things about how we relate to various things in our society, which in a sense we've sort of just taken for granted and we never sort of question them.

130
00:14:17,726 --> 00:14:19,308
So just that sense of

131
00:14:19,626 --> 00:14:26,998
relationship to our wonderful politicians and this whole business of Brexit, which has overtaken us.

132
00:14:27,778 --> 00:14:31,884
And to recognize what is our response to that.

133
00:14:32,826 --> 00:14:39,134
And to all the troubles that our society has or the world has, how are we relating to it?

134
00:14:39,615 --> 00:14:45,123
Take the problem of, well not the problem, but take the whole business of compassion.

135
00:14:46,686 --> 00:14:48,368
So it's interesting to note that

136
00:14:48,634 --> 00:14:59,490
Everybody knows about the refugee crisis and the fact that people around the middle belt of the earth are beginning to suffer a bit more than us from climate change.

137
00:15:00,291 --> 00:15:06,558
And that there's a natural desire for people to move away, to look after themselves.

138
00:15:07,701 --> 00:15:11,505
And for the most part, there's a knowledge of that.

139
00:15:12,067 --> 00:15:16,852
And there may be some natural feeling of wanting to have help.

140
00:15:17,086 --> 00:15:27,062
sometimes not really accepting our fear of them, you know, that suddenly everybody is pouring into Europe, you know, why don't we go to China?

141
00:15:29,345 --> 00:15:33,951
So you get this sort of confusion of feelings about the refugees.

142
00:15:34,273 --> 00:15:45,269
And then suddenly, as you know, we had this terrible little picture of this little boy who drowned in the ocean and Angela Merkel is inviting a million

143
00:15:45,756 --> 00:15:47,499
refugees into Germany.

144
00:15:48,921 --> 00:16:04,523
So somewhere along the line that compassion has moved away from just a sort of knowing to a direct experience which is awoken within us, that sense of wanting to do something about a situation.

145
00:16:07,307 --> 00:16:15,038
So this business of ethics, it begins

146
00:16:15,371 --> 00:16:43,083
right there with that sense of self that sense of self is because it identifies so much with the body you'll notice here in this particular discourse that he says that the the the the mindfulness directed to the body so how important is the body in our lives now you might say well that's pretty obvious it's straightforward but can you think of anything that hasn't come through your body

147
00:16:45,476 --> 00:16:55,128
I mean, it's quite obvious that anything physical comes through your body, what you eat, etc., your exercise and your eyes and everything that you see.

148
00:16:55,148 --> 00:17:08,682
But everything else, all the information that we get from society, all the information that we get through our relationships to people is all coming through the body, through the ears, through the brain, into the mind.

149
00:17:09,220 --> 00:17:16,009
So the body is absolutely, it's our basic sense of being in the world.

150
00:17:17,049 --> 00:17:25,460
And we know how desperate that can become when the body falls ill and we find ourselves close up to death.

151
00:17:26,582 --> 00:17:27,803
That's when the shaking comes.

152
00:17:27,863 --> 00:17:32,048
That's when the horror of our situation arises in our mind.

153
00:17:32,789 --> 00:17:38,636
So this relationship that we have, this sense of self, also has

154
00:17:38,920 --> 00:17:46,210
it first of all mirrors back to us that sense of consciousness or awareness.

155
00:17:46,931 --> 00:17:51,135
Be careful with words because they have all sorts of meanings, but that sense of awareness.

156
00:17:52,298 --> 00:18:00,929
And that sense of awareness has a sense of itself, of itself being aware.

157
00:18:01,569 --> 00:18:07,678
But that sense of itself being aware is a mirror of that awareness within the mind itself.

158
00:18:08,468 --> 00:18:21,364
And so what happens is that seeking happiness, it goes, as it were, through that sense of self into the psychophysical organism and begins to feed itself to make itself feel happy and comfortable.

159
00:18:21,984 --> 00:18:29,534
And then, of course, it's up against the world, which is ready to offer all those things to us.

160
00:18:30,494 --> 00:18:32,979
We begin to accumulate.

161
00:18:33,699 --> 00:18:35,741
Now, because...

162
00:18:36,008 --> 00:18:48,266
this awareness wakes up and begins to realize that, in fact, things are impermanent, that sense of impermanence undermines that quality of happiness.

163
00:18:48,826 --> 00:18:53,134
So every time it accumulates something, there's always a fear of loss.

164
00:18:53,534 --> 00:18:56,598
The fear of loss means that you've got to accumulate more.

165
00:18:56,916 --> 00:19:01,423
So a lot of our acquisitiveness is about making ourselves feel safe.

166
00:19:01,443 --> 00:19:03,606
It's not just about enjoying things.

167
00:19:03,686 --> 00:19:10,156
It's about making ourselves feel secure within a world that we're not certain about what's going to happen next.

168
00:19:11,138 --> 00:19:23,176
And once you're dependent upon what you have for your sense of security, anything that undermines that becomes your enemy and your aversion arises quite naturally.

169
00:19:23,748 --> 00:19:26,912
And when that enemy is a bit bigger than you, then you've got to run for it.

170
00:19:27,452 --> 00:19:37,386
So those three attitudes arise out of this false sense of self-acquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

171
00:19:38,307 --> 00:19:44,757
And it's from that base when we're feeling agitated or when we're feeling threatened, that's where we work from.

172
00:19:45,979 --> 00:19:47,780
Once we behave from that base,

173
00:19:48,165 --> 00:19:56,336
Then, of course, we produce certain habits within us, certain mental states, certain conditions that we call karma or consequences.

174
00:19:57,278 --> 00:20:08,875
And there's a second tier, you might say, of suffering that comes from that agitation, which is, of course, guilt, shame.

175
00:20:09,479 --> 00:20:16,588
and the comeback from other people who see you as selfish and not generous, etc.

176
00:20:16,970 --> 00:20:21,556
See you as not compassionate enough, see you as not loving enough.

177
00:20:21,896 --> 00:20:32,932
So, all those maladies arise from a mistake, from a mistake that goes so deep that we're not aware of it.

178
00:20:33,492 --> 00:20:36,416
And it all comes back down into that sense of self.

179
00:20:37,218 --> 00:20:38,440
So,

180
00:20:38,875 --> 00:20:44,345
When we're meditating, we're trying to get down to that.

181
00:20:44,404 --> 00:20:46,990
We're first of all trying to purify the heart.

182
00:20:47,009 --> 00:20:56,428
So remember that the way that the process works in purifying the heart is to allow the heart to express its turbulences.

183
00:20:56,999 --> 00:21:14,396
So where we find anxiety, a sense of depression, sadness, grief, overexcitement, a desire to indulge, et cetera, where that comes out of the heart, remember, it's always seeking to satisfy itself.

184
00:21:15,377 --> 00:21:22,484
And one of the insights that we have is that that sort of desire is insatiable.

185
00:21:23,005 --> 00:21:24,626
It can never have enough.

186
00:21:25,096 --> 00:21:33,503
Partly because it's enjoyable and partly because we want more of it, meaning that there's a lesser chance of losing it.

187
00:21:34,104 --> 00:21:36,306
So there's always that sense of safety about things.

188
00:21:37,287 --> 00:21:41,790
So when these things come up in the mind, we have to be very careful.

189
00:21:42,090 --> 00:21:47,736
I should say come up in the heart as an emotional mood state.

190
00:21:47,756 --> 00:21:53,060
When it comes up in the heart, I have to be very careful not to let it grasp hold of the mind and create a story.

191
00:21:53,445 --> 00:21:59,973
Because that's how we begin to recognize that these things develop themselves, even in ordinary daily life, not just sitting.

192
00:22:00,193 --> 00:22:08,663
Just when you find yourself dreaming, where you're not doing very much, you're sitting in a chair or you're traveling somewhere on a bus or something.

193
00:22:08,963 --> 00:22:14,931
And the mind's just wandering, wandering, getting hold on its old usual habitual little ways of thinking.

194
00:22:15,530 --> 00:22:22,980
And you've got to come off that because we have to wake up to ourselves to realize that every time it does that, I'm just making things worse for myself.

195
00:22:23,652 --> 00:22:31,099
So coming back into the heart, we allow these emotional states, these turbulences to express themselves.

196
00:22:31,119 --> 00:22:33,823
And of course, that's the difficult part of our practice.

197
00:22:33,863 --> 00:22:34,723
It's not very pleasant.

198
00:22:35,125 --> 00:22:36,086
We have to stay with that.

199
00:22:36,105 --> 00:22:40,750
We have to wait until they begin to exhaust themselves.

200
00:22:41,672 --> 00:22:46,217
And it's important at least once or twice

201
00:22:46,585 --> 00:22:52,038
to wait until it completely ends, to wait till that process of turbulence completely ends.

202
00:22:52,097 --> 00:22:58,432
Because when it completely ends, what you get is your present, what you get is the consequence.

203
00:22:58,813 --> 00:23:04,205
And what you see clearly is that what you're suffering from moves towards its opposite.

204
00:23:04,607 --> 00:23:19,546
So, whereas once you've got all this agitation, this sort of, shall we say, a lot of anger about something, if you wait until the anger completely disappears, you find your perspective changes completely and you're able to see the other side.

205
00:23:19,945 --> 00:23:22,088
In other words, love arises quite naturally.

206
00:23:22,128 --> 00:23:26,913
It's the same with any cruel thoughts we have or any selfish thoughts.

207
00:23:27,394 --> 00:23:33,281
If you wait until the end of that, you see, then the opposite arises quite naturally.

208
00:23:33,817 --> 00:23:51,255
And if you can just do it enough times to convince yourself that that's what actually happens, then you get that inner conviction, that inner determination to actually, you know, stay with the turbulence of the heart until they heal themselves.

209
00:23:52,236 --> 00:23:55,959
That's an important sort of insight, psychotherapeutic insight, you might say.

210
00:23:57,701 --> 00:24:01,664
But in terms of this deeper malaise, this sense of self,

211
00:24:02,269 --> 00:24:09,119
then that comes out in that more inward state when we're sitting.

212
00:24:09,721 --> 00:24:16,269
And when he would have been sitting under the tree, when he suddenly saw that that sense of self was completely manufactured.

213
00:24:17,031 --> 00:24:19,054
It's manufactured moment after moment.

214
00:24:19,134 --> 00:24:21,999
It's not something that is always there.

215
00:24:22,500 --> 00:24:31,752
And that's the huge insight for us, because normally speaking, we have a sense of continuity, sense of substantiality of this me all the time.

216
00:24:32,375 --> 00:24:42,949
And by seeing that the self arises only within a process, only within a process does the Buddha realize that actually it has no base at all.

217
00:24:43,849 --> 00:24:47,875
And that sense of self, remember, is a relationship, right?

218
00:24:47,895 --> 00:24:54,203
It's that sense of me being here, me, that sense of me, yeah?

219
00:24:54,223 --> 00:25:00,271
So you can see that our practice has developed

220
00:25:00,421 --> 00:25:11,343
Both these two sides, it has the side of purifying the heart and the side of insight, the sight of actually seeing where this fundamental problem lies.

221
00:25:12,244 --> 00:25:22,125
And these adjectives are pointing to what happens when the self completely disappears and there is just that awareness.

222
00:25:22,797 --> 00:25:25,500
So now he's pointing to something which is transcendent.

223
00:25:26,101 --> 00:25:31,147
And he's telling us, he's saying that it's a wonderful thing, but he can't describe it.

224
00:25:31,167 --> 00:25:33,029
It's beyond description.

225
00:25:33,451 --> 00:25:40,098
But his words are the uninclined, which means that it's no longer seeking for something.

226
00:25:40,740 --> 00:25:43,063
So that statement, no longer seeking something.

227
00:25:43,083 --> 00:25:52,315
That statement that by the nun who was liberated, I've got up there, Meichi Kyao,

228
00:25:52,597 --> 00:25:54,221
Meichi just means a nun.

229
00:25:54,942 --> 00:25:55,682
Kya is a name.

230
00:25:56,002 --> 00:25:57,025
I think I pronounced it right.

231
00:25:58,446 --> 00:26:07,842
Expresses, she expresses quite clearly, you know, what that state is once you're liberated from that deep delusion.

232
00:26:08,522 --> 00:26:14,852
So this sense, this awareness is no longer inclined to try and seek happiness in the world.

233
00:26:15,973 --> 00:26:16,875
It's taintless.

234
00:26:16,895 --> 00:26:19,720
So these taints are

235
00:26:19,919 --> 00:26:32,597
They refer to something quite deep, the desire to become, the desire to continue, the desire for sensual pleasure, and that fundamental ignorance that we suffer from of not knowing who or what we really are.

236
00:26:33,579 --> 00:26:35,162
So those have gone.

237
00:26:35,782 --> 00:26:41,873
The truth by which he means something that is irrefutable.

238
00:26:43,234 --> 00:26:48,001
The far shore, that's one of his regular sort of...

239
00:26:48,438 --> 00:26:59,172
descriptions of it, the island, you're going beyond, over the sea of troubles, etc, etc, to a completely different place, right?

240
00:26:59,192 --> 00:27:00,113
It's transcendent.

241
00:27:00,874 --> 00:27:03,096
The subtle, the very difficult to see.

242
00:27:03,156 --> 00:27:13,490
So again, the reason why it's so subtle is because we identify with this sense of self, with being our self.

243
00:27:14,411 --> 00:27:15,913
That sense of identity

244
00:27:16,078 --> 00:27:20,506
is when you lose your objective view of things.

245
00:27:21,126 --> 00:27:26,795
So, for instance, if you're angry, you can be aware of being angry, but then suddenly you can lose it and rage.

246
00:27:27,355 --> 00:27:36,670
So that point of raging is a point where you completely identify with that mental state, and then you've lost all objectivity, you know?

247
00:27:39,146 --> 00:27:48,978
The unaging, so there's no, I mean, that's what he found, that there was, in that state there's no birth, there's no death, etc., there's no aging.

248
00:27:49,558 --> 00:27:51,602
It's stable, there's nothing moving in it.

249
00:27:52,301 --> 00:27:55,926
It's not disintegrating, it is completely substantial.

250
00:27:57,067 --> 00:27:58,690
It's the unmanifest.

251
00:27:58,809 --> 00:28:02,875
Now that's an interesting thing, that it can't be seen, right?

252
00:28:02,894 --> 00:28:07,500
You cannot see, you cannot hear or feel or know Nibbana as an object.

253
00:28:08,897 --> 00:28:11,039
The the unproliferated.

254
00:28:11,140 --> 00:28:14,282
So it's just it's not it's not one thing or two things.

255
00:28:14,423 --> 00:28:18,748
It's it's it's just in itself, just pure awareness.

256
00:28:19,548 --> 00:28:27,676
It's the peaceful, the deathless, which same as the unaging, the sublime, the auspicious, the secure.

257
00:28:28,217 --> 00:28:38,667
So that's this business of always feeling, you know, that sense underneath it of our existence, of being insecure, insecure against sickness, aging and death.

258
00:28:38,951 --> 00:28:40,534
So all that's completely gone.

259
00:28:41,414 --> 00:28:47,143
It's un-ailing in the sense that there's no suffering there from being sick or being ill.

260
00:28:48,825 --> 00:28:49,905
He calls it Nibbāna.

261
00:28:49,945 --> 00:28:54,451
Nibbāna has, well, it's defined as two sort of general meanings.

262
00:28:54,471 --> 00:28:57,636
That is, you're liberated from that wrong desire.

263
00:28:58,778 --> 00:29:01,461
So remember, there's two types of desire.

264
00:29:01,481 --> 00:29:07,068
So when the Buddha can see that somebody's come to him with a question which is troubling,

265
00:29:07,436 --> 00:29:08,778
there's a desire to help.

266
00:29:08,919 --> 00:29:17,590
So compassion, sympathetic joy, love, all those basic wholesome attitudes are still there.

267
00:29:17,632 --> 00:29:19,634
All the unwholesome ones have gone.

268
00:29:21,777 --> 00:29:25,301
It's the unafflicted, that's just saying there's no more suffering there.

269
00:29:26,683 --> 00:29:31,250
Dispassion, meaning here that you don't get caught up in other people's problems.

270
00:29:31,550 --> 00:29:33,394
There's not that reactivity.

271
00:29:34,116 --> 00:29:37,020
Purity, purity in an ethical sense.

272
00:29:38,022 --> 00:29:41,488
There's no more negativity within that state.

273
00:29:42,430 --> 00:29:47,096
Freedom, now that freedom is not the freedom to do something, it's the freedom from.

274
00:29:47,657 --> 00:29:51,002
It's the freedom from these wrong desires, from these painful desires.

275
00:29:51,723 --> 00:29:53,646
And that's another way of saying non-attachment.

276
00:29:54,387 --> 00:29:57,593
And then he says the island, which again links to this other shore.

277
00:29:58,413 --> 00:30:02,200
The island, something which is completely separate unto itself.

278
00:30:02,752 --> 00:30:05,536
not attached to the land, not attached to anything else.

279
00:30:06,676 --> 00:30:08,798
And the shelter, so there's your safety.

280
00:30:08,838 --> 00:30:10,421
It's the asylum, the refuge.

281
00:30:11,301 --> 00:30:15,665
All these are telling us that once you're there, you simply can't suffer.

282
00:30:15,967 --> 00:30:24,816
You've gone beyond the ability to engage in the world that you find yourself in, in a way that is going to cause you suffering.

283
00:30:24,836 --> 00:30:28,259
There's a sort of profound liberation.

284
00:30:28,839 --> 00:30:31,663
It's the destination, the path leading to the destination.

285
00:30:34,124 --> 00:30:44,586
So his description often of that end game is more negative than positive.

286
00:30:44,625 --> 00:30:48,273
This is quite something to come across in the scriptures.

287
00:30:48,314 --> 00:30:54,326
I think there's only one other place where so many adjectives are put, about 32 of them or something.

288
00:30:54,880 --> 00:31:01,912
put in a way that has both that negative side of what it's not and the positive side of what it is.

289
00:31:02,492 --> 00:31:09,986
But when you put all those ideas together, they never sum up to the actual experience of Nirvana.

290
00:31:10,807 --> 00:31:14,133
So how do we get a feel for it?

291
00:31:14,192 --> 00:31:16,737
How do we get a sense of what Nirvana might be?

292
00:31:17,678 --> 00:31:28,453
So in your practice, when you're sitting there, you might come across this, you know, this deep sense of stillness, a deep sense of silence within yourself, even if only for a moment.

293
00:31:29,174 --> 00:31:40,092
And as you as you as that appears within you, that comes to you and you get that sense of you being in the midst of that, a sense of the observer, the feeler, you see.

294
00:31:40,695 --> 00:31:51,493
just for a moment there, just become, as it were, internally aware of that sense of self, of the sense of the feeler, and just ask yourself, what's it made of?

295
00:31:53,076 --> 00:32:03,213
And that's when you begin to recognize that the awareness is something quite separate from all the other things that you can experience through the body.

296
00:32:04,336 --> 00:32:06,720
All our emotions and moods,

297
00:32:06,903 --> 00:32:28,724
are through the body all our imagination and thought are through the body through the brain all our physical feelings are through the body so the body is there as a sort of basic platform upon which we experience things experience everything that in this world it comes through the body and it's of the body yeah

298
00:32:29,244 --> 00:32:38,234
And here you are, as it were, separated within yourself into this observation post, this sort of platform within yourself where you can see all this.

299
00:32:38,555 --> 00:32:39,576
You're separate from it.

300
00:32:40,116 --> 00:32:46,784
And in moments of real peacefulness and calm, that sense of self becomes very clear, the observer.

301
00:32:47,244 --> 00:32:59,218
And it's just a case of holding that long enough to, as it were, glance inwards and just see what is that awareness made of, what's inside the awareness.

302
00:32:59,823 --> 00:33:03,747
And that gives us a clue as to what our destination is.

303
00:33:04,686 --> 00:33:18,720
So when the Buddha had discovered this, of course, he spent, so it says, he spent something like seven days, seven nights, just going through that whole process and thinking about it, reflecting on it.

304
00:33:19,560 --> 00:33:29,069
And from then on, he spent his 40 odd years, 45 years, 40 years, 45 years, teaching, wandering around North India.

305
00:33:29,843 --> 00:33:52,056
When you read the scriptures, that wandering really, really comes out because as he's going from place to place and he's being asked questions by people, this word, how to describe the mind becomes very, it's very undefined.

306
00:33:52,455 --> 00:33:56,221
So the word consciousness is used in many ways.

307
00:33:56,506 --> 00:34:05,494
It's used as just a screen upon which something happens, but it's also used as a sort of discriminative process, an understanding process.

308
00:34:05,935 --> 00:34:16,847
The word citta, which is another word for consciousness, is used also as a sort of awareness, but it's also used as your emotional base, your mental state.

309
00:34:17,887 --> 00:34:26,277
And it's only by really doing the practice that these things begin to clarify themselves.

310
00:34:26,594 --> 00:34:37,108
and why he sort of began to deconstruct our experience into these, what he called these five aggregates.

311
00:34:37,650 --> 00:34:49,347
All those things to do with the body, our direct physicality, such as pure tasting, movement, the sense of cold and heat and all that.

312
00:34:50,128 --> 00:34:52,331
And then there's a whole section about feeling.

313
00:34:52,811 --> 00:34:55,014
And feeling, the one word, covers both

314
00:34:55,213 --> 00:35:03,105
the physical feelings and the mental feelings, how we feel inside ourselves with various different emotions or moods.

315
00:35:03,465 --> 00:35:09,273
And that was a whole, he separated that out from the actual sensations that come directly from the body.

316
00:35:09,954 --> 00:35:18,485
So the body and mind in Buddhist teaching, remember, are two different things, but they work, the one saturates the other.

317
00:35:18,525 --> 00:35:21,469
You can't really separate them by way of experience.

318
00:35:22,670 --> 00:35:24,293
And then there's a whole process of

319
00:35:24,474 --> 00:35:31,987
mentation, how we're able to create symbols in the mind, images in the mind, which

320
00:35:32,152 --> 00:35:37,159
through various, which through more and more experience become concepts.

321
00:35:37,798 --> 00:35:41,623
So as soon as a child, we would have seen a spider.

322
00:35:42,204 --> 00:35:49,052
And then after a lot of seeing of spiders and pictures and all that, we've ended up with a concept of a spider in our mind.

323
00:35:49,592 --> 00:35:51,835
So as soon as we see a spider, we'll name it.

324
00:35:51,856 --> 00:35:53,336
We'll know what it is, a spider.

325
00:35:53,657 --> 00:35:54,838
But we won't actually look at it.

326
00:35:55,159 --> 00:35:58,362
And very few of us are capable of actually feeling it.

327
00:35:58,764 --> 00:36:08,012
So it's a case of recognizing that there's a sort of mismatch comes through the process of conceptualization.

328
00:36:08,432 --> 00:36:13,318
And that's a section of these aggregates.

329
00:36:13,777 --> 00:36:17,762
Then there comes this whole section of habituation, of habits.

330
00:36:18,541 --> 00:36:27,489
And this is crucial in the way that he separates that because these are something that we actively create through our will.

331
00:36:27,536 --> 00:36:35,664
And that's where the suffering lies, in these sankharas, these compounded things that we've created.

332
00:36:35,965 --> 00:36:38,746
Well, we call them our habits, volitional activities.

333
00:36:39,748 --> 00:36:42,210
And then there's consciousness, you see.

334
00:36:42,891 --> 00:36:46,914
And then beyond that, there's this sense of awareness.

335
00:36:47,856 --> 00:36:55,603
And that sometimes you might find confusing in a lot of Buddhist literature because often writers don't make that distinction.

336
00:36:56,056 --> 00:37:09,295
And what happens is then the idea of nibbana becomes something so abstract, it's sort of outside our ability to even get a glimpse of it.

337
00:37:10,277 --> 00:37:18,148
So long as awareness is confused with consciousness, then it's not possible to see what nibbana might be.

338
00:37:18,297 --> 00:37:36,637
It's only when we begin to realize or recognize or open up to the possibility that awareness is not the same as consciousness that then there becomes this insight into what might be transcendent of our psychophysical organism.

339
00:37:38,820 --> 00:37:46,548
So consciousness is really just that screen upon which we're seeing and experiencing everything.

340
00:37:47,119 --> 00:37:48,001
But we're right in it.

341
00:37:48,061 --> 00:37:50,262
It's like our face is in the monitor.

342
00:37:51,184 --> 00:37:52,266
It's not separate from it.

343
00:37:52,346 --> 00:37:53,766
It's not outside the monitor.

344
00:37:54,447 --> 00:37:57,391
Your face is in the monitor, in the monitor screen.

345
00:37:57,791 --> 00:37:59,052
That's what it is.

346
00:37:59,092 --> 00:38:10,204
And every time you pull out, every time you sit back into your desk and begin to recognize that you're watching a monitor, that's what you're doing when you're sitting in meditation.

347
00:38:10,224 --> 00:38:10,865
You're pulling out.

348
00:38:11,672 --> 00:38:17,639
And that sense of self is, again, a mirror image of awareness on that screen.

349
00:38:18,179 --> 00:38:26,967
And the best example was given to me by Noreen, really, when talking about looking into shops when you're doing shopping.

350
00:38:27,407 --> 00:38:36,436
So when you look in there and you see all these lovely things, you might catch your own mirror image looking at you looking into the shop.

351
00:38:36,777 --> 00:38:41,561
And if you stop for a minute, you can actually comb your hair in the mirror.

352
00:38:41,947 --> 00:38:43,128
It's that, well, I used to.

353
00:38:45,090 --> 00:38:53,201
So that sense of mirror image is exactly what we mean by this self-awareness at its original apparition.

354
00:38:53,961 --> 00:39:05,056
And it's through that consciousness of that screen, of that window on the shop, you see, that you're entering into all this shopping.

355
00:39:05,476 --> 00:39:09,402
And I wonder we have, what's it called?

356
00:39:09,762 --> 00:39:10,923
Shopping therapy or something.

357
00:39:11,257 --> 00:39:14,961
It's all there as you walk down the high street.

358
00:39:14,981 --> 00:39:23,211
So just to try and pull all that together, the Buddha teaches two things.

359
00:39:23,231 --> 00:39:30,800
You can categorize them as two major teachings, ethics and transcendence.

360
00:39:30,880 --> 00:39:36,927
The transcendence is just a little bit because you can't say that much about it, but you can describe the path leading to it.

361
00:39:37,650 --> 00:39:41,876
And he points out that the fundamental problem is one of identity.

362
00:39:42,057 --> 00:39:47,606
It goes back to that ancient Greek thing of know yourself or who am I?

363
00:39:47,626 --> 00:39:52,552
That's the deepest question we have, really, of who am I?

364
00:39:53,594 --> 00:39:57,920
And this who am I manifests itself.

365
00:39:58,222 --> 00:40:06,574
outwardly as a connection with the world it finds itself in, in a way which creates suffering for itself.

366
00:40:06,614 --> 00:40:08,998
That's the sort of peculiar situation we're in.

367
00:40:09,579 --> 00:40:17,552
We're seeking happiness, but because it's not in the right way, it rebounds back to us as a sense of unsatisfactoriness.

368
00:40:17,572 --> 00:40:21,858
You just can't get out of life what you would like to get out of life as a constant.

369
00:40:22,360 --> 00:40:24,262
You can hold it for a second or two and that's it.

370
00:40:25,103 --> 00:40:31,909
And then we begin to let go of all that, begin to allow it to manifest as turbulences in the heart.

371
00:40:31,929 --> 00:40:38,577
And as that purification becomes more and more within us, there's a growth in virtue.

372
00:40:39,197 --> 00:40:44,885
And the Buddha equates ordinary mundane happiness with virtue.

373
00:40:45,264 --> 00:40:47,847
The more virtuous we are, the more happy we are.

374
00:40:48,347 --> 00:40:52,612
So you can always begin to, shall we say, examine

375
00:40:52,811 --> 00:40:58,018
We can always examine our lives by asking ourselves, well, exactly how generous am I?

376
00:40:58,039 --> 00:40:59,920
Exactly how loving am I?

377
00:40:59,981 --> 00:41:01,684
How compassionate am I?

378
00:41:02,565 --> 00:41:06,570
And these are all little telltales to us that we're moving along the path.

379
00:41:06,590 --> 00:41:15,742
So the first part, the first of the path is right understanding.

380
00:41:16,282 --> 00:41:21,570
And that's basically the point of this insight business and understanding the teachings.

381
00:41:22,242 --> 00:41:25,306
Underneath that, there comes immediately right attitude.

382
00:41:26,045 --> 00:41:33,695
And right attitude is normally written as from selfishness to generosity, from hatred to love, from cruelty to compassion.

383
00:41:34,056 --> 00:41:37,179
But any negativity you have moves towards its opposite.

384
00:41:37,599 --> 00:41:49,072
But you can see that you can undermine this sense of self by going the other way, by practicing, by developing generosity, love, compassion, etc., etc.

385
00:41:49,494 --> 00:41:50,594
You're undermining that.

386
00:41:50,827 --> 00:41:52,309
the sense of self.

387
00:41:52,929 --> 00:41:53,251
How?

388
00:41:53,530 --> 00:42:00,179
Because you're beginning to recognize that we're not an identity, we're not separate from the world around us.

389
00:42:01,079 --> 00:42:11,931
And that undoing of that sort of barrier between me and somebody else is part of undoing this concept of a self, of who I am.

390
00:42:12,873 --> 00:42:17,898
And eventually that identification, you might say,

391
00:42:18,250 --> 00:42:21,253
with all beings is the manifestation of love.

392
00:42:21,413 --> 00:42:24,114
It's what we practice when we say metta.

393
00:42:24,615 --> 00:42:25,836
May all beings be happy.

394
00:42:25,856 --> 00:42:26,958
It includes me as well.

395
00:42:27,498 --> 00:42:28,498
So I'm in there.

396
00:42:28,679 --> 00:42:29,880
I'm in the mix.

397
00:42:29,900 --> 00:42:37,387
And it's me trying to find a relationship whereby I'm not coming from me all the time.

398
00:42:37,447 --> 00:42:40,269
I'm coming from a sense of we and a sense of you.

399
00:42:41,010 --> 00:42:46,536
The Buddha put it nicely as that we do things for ourselves, for others, for both ourselves and others.

400
00:42:47,224 --> 00:42:53,795
When we begin to behave in that more virtuous way, that sense of self begins to dissipate.

401
00:42:54,956 --> 00:43:02,829
There begins that communication, you might say, between us, between others, between nature.

402
00:43:03,891 --> 00:43:12,945
And that is beginning to understand how we can live in the world whereby we're no longer suffering from it.

403
00:43:13,650 --> 00:43:16,233
So that's something to sort of contemplate.

404
00:43:16,253 --> 00:43:17,635
The Buddha doesn't actually suffer.

405
00:43:18,375 --> 00:43:22,119
Not that he fell ill. As you know, he growled, he died.

406
00:43:22,159 --> 00:43:25,101
He went through all the processes that we would go through.

407
00:43:26,101 --> 00:43:29,465
But none of it was his suffering.

408
00:43:29,485 --> 00:43:35,891
And I would really invite you to read that statement by the nun because she says it so perfectly.

409
00:43:36,391 --> 00:43:36,632
You see?

410
00:43:37,413 --> 00:43:37,693
You see?

411
00:43:37,913 --> 00:43:42,197
Even the cat understands.

412
00:43:42,217 --> 00:43:43,117
Very, very...

413
00:43:43,282 --> 00:43:45,425
The peculiar cat is from next door, you know.

414
00:43:46,706 --> 00:43:50,471
I blame it on John, he used to greet it, you know.

415
00:43:51,692 --> 00:43:55,376
I have a horror of cats.

416
00:43:55,396 --> 00:44:02,003
Mainly because they always leave the field with a mouse in there, or some sort of animal in their mouths, you know.

417
00:44:02,505 --> 00:44:03,786
And it's not as though they're not fed.

418
00:44:04,766 --> 00:44:07,349
You call Buddy, by the way.

419
00:44:08,748 --> 00:44:22,612
So anyway, I hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused even greater confusion, and that you will, by your complete devotion to the practice, liberate yourselves from all suffering, sooner rather than later.

420
00:44:26,358 --> 00:44:29,083
Yes, you can say Sadi.

421
00:44:29,103 --> 00:44:31,126
Sadi, Sadi.

